# Lesson 2 - Paths

## Absolute Path

An absolute path always starts from the root directory (`/`).

It works regardless of your current location.

### Example

```bash
cd /home/hamad/linux-practice/backups
```

---

## Relative Path

A relative path depends on your current directory.

### Example

If you are in:

```text
/home/hamad/linux-practice
```

You can access:

```bash
cd projects/project1
```

---

## Special Directory Symbols

### .

Represents the current directory.

```bash
cd .
```

Usually used with commands such as:

```bash
find .
```

or

```bash
./script.sh
```

---

### ..

Represents the parent directory.

Example:

```bash
cd ..
```

If you are in:

```text
/home/hamad/linux-practice/backups
```

After running:

```bash
cd ..
```

You will be in:

```text
/home/hamad/linux-practice
```

---

### ~

Represents the current user's home directory.

Example:

```bash
cd ~
```

Result:

```text
/home/hamad
```

